    <h1>Opportunities with Brain-Computer Interfaces</h1>

    <div class="opportunity-section">
        <div class="text">
            <p>Brain-Computer Interfaces are a remarkable technological breakthrough, creating a direct link between the brain and external devices. One of their most promising uses is in the medical field. For people with physical disabilities such as those affected by spinal cord injuries or conditions like ALS, BCIs offer new levels of independence. These systems can help individuals control prosthetic limbs, operate wheelchairs, or communicate using computer systems, all by using their thoughts.</p>

            <p>Beyond healthcare, BCIs have the potential to transform everyday interactions with technology. Imagine being able to operate your phone, computer, or smart home appliances just by thinking. This kind of hands-free control could make technology more intuitive and efficient. BCIs are also gaining popularity in gaming and virtual reality, offering deeply immersive experiences where users can influence gameplay through focus or emotional state.</p>

            <p>Another exciting area is cognitive enhancement. Though still in early stages, researchers are exploring how BCIs might improve memory, focus, and learning abilities by stimulating certain parts of the brain. This could eventually support educational tools or mental health therapies.</p>
        </div>
