        <div class="text">
            <p>Modern brain-computer interface research owes a lot to pioneers like Lebedev and Nicolelis (2017). Their work showed that it's possible to decode brain signals with impressive accuracy and turn them into commands for things like robotic arms. One of the big takeaways from their studies is how important it is to have systems that can adapt and learn just like the brain does. Thanks to neuroplasticity, people using BCIs can actually get better over time, making the control of devices feel more natural.</p>

            <p>Furthermore, the review by Lebedev and Nicolelis highlights the potential of BCIs in neurorehabilitation. For patients recovering from stroke or traumatic brain injury, BCIs could facilitate the retraining of motor pathways by providing real-time feedback and encouraging brain activity in damaged areas.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div >
        <h2>The Future of BCIs</h2>
        <p>As BCI technology grows, systems may unlock even more complex interactions, such as full-body exoskeletons controlled by thought or interfaces that assist with complex cognitive functions. These developments point toward a future in which BCIs are not just assistive, but also enhancing human potential in both clinical and everyday environments.</p>

        <p>While the future of BCIs is full of exciting possibilities, it also brings challenges. Issues like data privacy, informed consent, and the risk of becoming overly dependent on such technology need careful attention. Still, BCIs offer a glimpse into a future where the line between human thought and machine response becomes more fluid, ultimately aiming to improve the way we live and interact with the world.</p>
